{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514909"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12401"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12401"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.02,0.11,0.08,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99143"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4909"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81536"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43326"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99143"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of shortness of breath, chest tightness, and a cough. The cough is aggravated late at night and early in the morning. He had previous similar episodes of cough and shortness of breath after exposure to dust in the last 3-4 years, but they were mild and self-limiting. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears mildly distressed with a pulse rate of 85/min, blood pressure 135/89 mmHg, respiratory rate 25/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His chest has audible wheezing and decreased breath sounds in both lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spirometry","Sputum MCS","High resolution CT chest","Serum allergy test","ECG"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms of this patient, including aggravation by dust and wheezes in the lungs, are consistent with the diagnosis of asthma. \u003Cstrong\u003ESpirometry\u003C/strong\u003E (pre/post bronchodilator FEV1 specifically) is the diagnostic investigation for this condition. Typically, an improvement in FEV1 post-bronchodilator of at least 12% and 200 mL from baseline can be used to diagnose asthma, although asthma can be made clinically or via other investigations even without this spirometry result. Spirometry also helps to monitor asthma and to assess the effectiveness of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh resolution computed tomography scan (HRCT)\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly used to diagnose interstitial lung disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, lung fibrosis, lung tumours, etc, but it is not usually used as a diagnostic tool for asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum allergy\u003C/strong\u003E test is a blood test that measures Ige levels in blood. A high IgE level indicates an allergic response of the body against a particular allergen. It may support the diagnosis of asthma, but it is not solely used as a diagnostic tool.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an \u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate investigation to consider in a patient with tightness of the chest, an ischaemic cause would be unlikely in a 38-year-old man. In this case, the patient\u0027s symptoms are more towards asthma with wheezes on chest, normal pulse and a near normal blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum MCS\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if the primary problem were thought to be a lung infection, which is not the case here. It can also be used in the assessment of asthma, but is not primarily used as a diagnostic tool.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spirometry with bronchodilator reversibility testing is the diagnostic tool for asthma, with a significant response defined as an increase in FEV1 of \u226510% of predicted value.","Asthma symptoms often worsen at night and early in the morning due to circadian variations in airway tone and reactivity.","Wheezing and shortness of breath triggered by allergens or irritants are characteristic of asthma."],"references":["Hashmi MF, Cataletto ME. Asthma. 2024 May 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613651. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28613651/","Celli BR. The importance of spirometry in COPD and asthma: effect on approach to management. Chest. 2000 Feb;117(2 Suppl):15S-9S. doi: 10.1378/chest.117.2_suppl.15s. PMID: 10673468. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10673468/","Brigham EP, West NE. Diagnosis of asthma: diagnostic testing. Int Forum Allergy Rhinol. 2015 Sep;5 Suppl 1:S27-30. doi: 10.1002/alr.21597. PMID: 26335833. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26335833/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81536"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12401"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"